\chapter{O-Telos by ConceptBase.cc}
\label{cap:language}

ConceptBase.cc is an implementation of the O-Telos data model.
O-Telos is derived from the knowledge representation language Telos as
designed by Borgida, Mylopoulos and others \cite{mbjk90}.
While Telos was geared more to its roots in artificial intelligence, O-Telos
is more geared to database theory, in particular to deductive databases.
Nevertheless, O-Telos is to a large degree compatible to the original
Telos specification. In some respects, it generalizes Telos, for example by
removing the requirement to classify objects into the levels for
tokens, simple classes, and meta classes.
In O-Telos, we have just five predefined objects (see appendix
on the axioms of O-Telos).

Telos (and O-Telos) as well also have strong links to the semantic web, in
particular to the triple predicates used for defining RDF(S) statements. The main
difference is that O-Telos is based on quadruples where the additional
components identifies the statement. While RDF(S) has to use special link
types to reify triple statements, i.e.\ to make statements about statements,
O-Telos statements are simply referred to by their identifier. 

Telos' structurally object-oriented framework generalizes earlier data
models and knowledge representation formalisms, such as entity-relationship
diagrams or semantic networks, and integrates them with predicative
assertions, temporal information, and in particular metamodeling.
This combination of features seems to
be particularly useful in software information applications such as
requirements modeling and software process control. A formal description of
O-Telos can be found in \cite{mbjk90,jeus92}. The following example is used
throughout this section to illustrate the language:


\begin{example}
    {}A company has {\tt employees\/}, some of them being {\tt
    managers\/}. Employees have a {\tt name\/} and a {\tt salary}
    which may change from time to time. They are assigned to {\tt
    departments} which are {\tt headed} by managers. The {\tt boss} of
    an employee can be derived from his department and the manager of
    that department. No employee is allowed to earn more money than his
    boss.
\end{example}

This section is organized as follows: first, the "logical" and "frame"
representations of O-Telos are explained. Then, the predicative
sublanguage for deductive rules and integrity constraints are presented.
Subsection \ref{sec:CBQL} presents a declarative query language which introduces
queries as classes with optional predicative membership specification.



\section{Propositions and frames}
\label{sec:representation}

As a hybrid language O-Telos supports two different representation formats:
a logical ("propositions") and a frame representation. The
latter format is based on the logical one.  As explained in the next
subsections the logical representation also forms the base for integrating
a predicative assertion language for deductive rules, queries, and
integrity constraints into the frame representation. We start with the
so-called P-fact representation of a O-Telos database.


A {\em historical\/} O-Telos database is a finite set of propositions
(=P-facts=objects):

$$  \OB = \{{\tt P(oid,x,n,y,tt)}| {\tt oid,x,y,tt} \in \ID, {\tt n} \in \LABEL\} $$

where {\tt oid} has the key property within the set,
$\ID$ is an infinite but countable set
of identifiers. The set  $\LABEL$ is a set of names over some alphabet. The components {\tt oid,
x, n, y, tt} are called identifier, source, label (or name), destination and
transaction time of the proposition%
\footnote{We will see in section \ref{sec:CBL} that the predicative language operates
on a snapshot of the database, i.e.\ on those propositions that
are believed at a specified reference time called rollback time. This time is an
interval. The of the interval is the time when the object has been told/created.
The end of the interval is either the time when the object was untold/deleted, or
it is a special symbol {\it infinity}, indicating that the object is currently believed, i.e. it is
not deleted.}%
. We read them as follows:

\begin{quote}
  The object {\tt x} has a relationship called {\tt n} to the object
  {\tt y}. This relationship is believed by the system for the time interval
  {\tt tt}.
\end{quote}


The transaction time {\tt tt} is represented by two time points $tt(a,b)$, where $a$ is
the time when the {\em tell\/} time and $b$ the {\em untell\/} time of the
P-fact. 
The historical O-Telos database is the basis for the {\em rollback\/} O-Telos database that
is visible at a given point of time. 


$$  \OB_{rbt} = \{{\tt P(oid,x,n,y)}| {\tt P(oid,x,n,y,tt)} \in \OB, {\tt rbt} \ll {\tt tt}\} $$

The clause  $t_1 \ll t_2$ expresses that the time interval $t_1$ is contained
in time interval $t_2$, i.e.\ $t_1$ is during $t_2$.
The value of the rollback time depends on the kind of formula to be
processed: integrity constraints are always evaluated against the {\em current\/} database
$\OB_{now}$%
\footnote{Only objects that have a right-open belief
time shall be visible $\OB_{now}$. This is due to the fact that the end time of an
object can only be changed once, namely when the object is untold. The UNTELL
operation can only have happened in the past when $OB_{now}$ is built.}
({\tt now}=the smallest time interval that contains the current time).
The rollback time of queries is usually provided together with the query
when it is submitted from a user interface to a ConceptBase server.
By default, it is {\it now} as well.
Subsequently, we shall use $\OB_{rbt}$ rather than {\OB}. Note that
$\OB_{rbt}$ strips the transaction time {\tt tt} from the P-facts. We shall still
call both a P-fact. Any P-fact from  $\OB_{rbt}$ has a unique counterpart
in {\OB}, hence the transaction time can always be looked up in {\OB}.
We demand that any $\OB_{rbt}$ is consistent but do not demand it
for the database {\OB}, which stores the whole history of updates.


O-Telos imposes some structural axioms on databases, e.g. referential
integrity, correct instantiation and inheritance (\cite{jeus92}). The
complete list of axioms is contained in appendix \ref{cha:otelos-axioms}.
The axioms are linked to predefined objects that are part of each O-Telos database.
There are five predefined O-Telos objects for five patterns of propositions:

\begin{itemize}

\item {\tt Proposition} contains all propositions as instances. A proposition
is any P-fact in an O-Telos database $\OB_{rbt}$
that has the form {\tt P(oid,x,n,y)}. Any proposition must fall into
exactly one of the subsequent cases.


\item {\tt Individual} is a the class of all P-Facts that have the form
{\tt P(oid,oid,n,oid)}. Such P-facts are denoted as nodes in the graphical
representation of an O-Telos database.

\item {\tt InstanceOf} contains all explicit instantiation objects as instances.
This is exactly the set of P-facts matching the pattern
{\tt P(oid,x,*instanceof,c)}. We say that {\tt x} is an (explicit)
instance of {\tt c}.
In the graphical representation, an instantiation object is a link
between some object {\tt x} and its class {\tt c}. Note that any such
explicit instantiation is also an object/proposition with identifier {\tt oid}.

\item {\tt IsA} contains all explicit specialization objects as instances.
Specialization P-facts match the pattern {\tt P(oid,c,*isa,d)}
A specialization object is graphically displayed as a link between
a subclass {\tt c} and its superclass {\tt d}.

\item {\tt Attribute} contains all explicit attribution/relation
objects as instances. An attribution/relation object matches the pattern
{\tt P(oid,x,m,y)} where {\tt m} must be different from 
{\tt *instanceof} and {\tt *isa}.
It is displayed by a link between the source object
{\tt x} and the destination object {\tt y}. The label of the attribution object
is the name of the attribute link starting from {\tt x}. The object
{\tt y} is also called the value or destination of the attribute.
In O-Telos, the class {\tt Attribute} subsumes relations between objects
since values are just objects in O-Telos. In ConceptBase, 
{\tt Attribute} is a shortcut for
{\tt Proposition!attribute}, i.e. the link {\tt attribute}
of {\tt Proposition}.

\end{itemize}

ConceptBase supports deductive rules for deriving the instantiation of an object to a class
and attributes/relations between objects. This derived information has no
object property, i.e. it is not identified and it is not represented as a
proposition. Specifically, the instantiation of propositions to the above
five pre-defined objects is derived by deductive rules, specifically by axioms 
18-22 in appendix \ref{cha:otelos-axioms}.

Additional to the above predefined classes%
\footnote{Strictly speaking, we should better use the term predefined object or
predefined proposition.}%
,
there are the builtin classes {\tt Class}, {\tt Integer}, {\tt Real} and {\tt String}.
{\tt Class} contains all so-called classes (including itself) as instances.
The only special property of {\tt Class} is the definition of two
attribute categories  {\tt rule} and {\tt constraint}.  Hence, instances of classes
can have deductive rules and integrity constraints.
Integer and real numbers are written in the usual way, strings are
character sequences, e.g. {\tt "this is a string"}.
These three classes are supported by comparison predicates like
{\tt (x < y)} discussed in section \ref{sec:CBL}, and by functions like
PLUS, MINUS discussed in section \ref{sec:functions}.

As legacy support, ConceptBase provides the pre-defined classes {\tt Token},
{\tt SimpleClass}, {\tt Meta\-Class}, and {\tt MetametaClass}
 to structure the database
into objects that have no instances (tokens), objects that have only tokens as
instances (simple classes), objects that have only simple classes as instances (meta classes),
and finally objects that have only meta classes as instances (meta meta classes).
These classes are provided only for
compatibility with older Telos specifications.  In fact, an absolute hierarchy from
tokens to simple classes to meta classes etc. is not an essential
ingredient of O-Telos and in many situations too restrictive.

Instead, meta class levels are
implicitely expressed via instantiation. If an object {\tt x} is an
instance of object {\tt c} and object {\tt c} is an instance of
object {\tt mc}, then {\tt mc} is also called a {\em meta class\/} of
{\tt x}, and {\tt c} a {\em class\/} of {\tt x}. Being a class or
a meta class is {\bf relative} to the object {\tt x} that we consider.
For example, {\tt mc} is the class of {\tt c}.
This implicit definition of the meta class concept is far more flexible
than a fixed structure:
\begin{enumerate}
\item There is virtually no limit in the meta class hierarchy: there can be meta
classes, meta meta classes, meta meta meta classes etc.
\item A class can have object from different meta class levels as instances.
This is in particular important for extending the capabilities of the O-Telos
language. An example of a class that has objects from different levels as
instances is {\tt Proposition}: it has {\em all\/} objects as instances.
\item A user does not need to decide to which meta class level
an object belongs.
\end{enumerate}
Strict conformance to the membership to meta class levels can still be enforced
by user-definable integrity constraints.


As a user, you don't work directly with propositions but with textual
(frame) and graphical (semantic networks) views on them. Both are not based
on the oid's of objects but on their label components. To guarantee a
unique mapping we need the following naming axiom:

\begin{axiom}{Naming axiom (see also axioms 2,3,4 in appendix \ref{cha:otelos-axioms})}
 \begin{enumerate}
  \item The label (``name'') of an individual object must be
  unique, i.e. if two objects have the same label than they are the same.
  \item The label of an attribute must be unique within all
  attributes with a common source object, i.e. no two explicit attributes
  of the same object can have the same label. However, two different objects
  can well have attributes sharing the same label.
  \item The source and destination of an instantiation object are unique, i.e. between
  two objects {\tt x} and {\tt y} may be at most one explicit instantiation link.
  \item The source and destination of a specialization object are unique.
 \end{enumerate}
\end{axiom}

The {\bf frame syntax} of O-Telos groups the labels of propositions with common
source {\tt o} around the label of {\tt o}. The exact syntax is given in appendix \ref{cha:syntax}.
In this section we introduce it by modeling the employee example:


\begin{verbatim}
Employee in Class with
   attribute
      name: String;
      salary: Integer;
      dept: Department;
      boss: Manager
end

Manager in Class isA Employee end

Department in Class with
   attribute
      head: Manager
end
\end{verbatim}


The label of the ``common source'' in the first frame is {\tt
  Employee}. It is declared as instance of the class {\tt Class} and has four
attributes. The class {\tt Manager} is a subclass of {\tt Employee}.

Oid's (preceded by `\#' in our examples) are generated by the system. This
leads to the following set of propositions corresponding to the frames
above. The transaction time inserted by the system is denoted by omission marks.


\begin{verbatim}
  P(#E,#E,Employee,#E)
  P(#1,#E,*instanceof,#Class)
  P(#3,#E,name,#String)
  P(#4,#E,salary,#Integer)
  P(#5,#E,dept,#D)
  P(#6,#E,boss,#M)
  P(#M,#M,Manager,#M)
  P(#7,#M,*instanceof,#Class)
  P(#8,#M,*isa,#E)
  P(#D,#D,Department,#D)
  P(#9,#D,*instanceof,#Class)
  P(#10,#D,head,#M)
\end{verbatim}

Instantiation to the pre-defined class {\tt Individual} is implicitly given by the
structure of the three individual propositions named {\tt Employee}, {\tt Manager},
 and {\tt Department}.  Analogously, the attributes {\tt
  \#3}, {\tt \#4}, {\tt \#5}, {\tt \#6} and {\tt \#10} are
automatically regarded as instances of the class {\tt Attribute}. 
The instances of {\tt Attribute} are also called {\em attribution objects\/}
or {\em explicit attributes}.
Propositions {\tt \#1}, {\tt \#2}, {\tt \#7} and {\tt \#9} are
instances of the class {\tt InstanceOf} (holding explicit instantiation objects), and {\tt \#8} is an instance
of the class {\tt IsA} (explicit specialization objects). Note that all relationships are declared by
using the identifiers (not the names) of objects. Thus, {\tt \#Class},
denotes the identifier of the object {\tt Class} etc.

The identifiers are maintained internally by ConceptBase's object store. Externally,
the user refers to objects by their name. A standard way to describe objects together
with their classes, subclasses, and attributes is the frame syntax. Frames
are uniformly based on object names.


The next frames establish two departments labelled {\tt PR} and
{\tt RD} and state that the individual object {\tt mary} is an
instance of the class {\tt Manager}. {\tt Mary} has four attributes
labelled {\tt hername}, {\tt earns}, {\tt advises} and {\tt
  currentdept} which are instances of the respective attribute classes
of {\tt Employee} with labels {\tt name}, {\tt salary} and {\tt dept}.


\begin{verbatim}
mary in Manager with
  name
    hername: "Mary Smith"
  salary
    earns: 15000
  dept
    advises:PR;
    currentdept:RD
end

PR in Department end

RD in Department end
\end{verbatim}


The corresponding propositions for the frame describing mary are:


\begin{verbatim}
  P(#mary,#mary,mary,#mary)
  P(#E1,#mary,*instanceof,#M)
  P(#E3,#mary,hername,"Mary Smith")
  P(#E4,#E3,*instanceof,#3)
  P(#E5,#mary,earns,15000)
  P(#E6,#E5,*instanceof,#4)
  P(#E7,#mary,advises,#PR)
  P(#E8,#E7,*instanceof,#5)
  P(#E10,#mary,currentdept,#RD)
  P(#E11,#E10,*instanceof,#5)
\end{verbatim}


  The attribute categories {\tt name, salary} and {\tt dept} must be defined in one of
    the classes of {\tt mary}. In this case mary is also instance of {\tt Employee} due to
the following axiom which defines the inheritance of class membership in
O-Telos, and hence can instantiate these attributes:

\begin{axiom}{Specialization axiom (axiom 13 in appendix \ref{cha:otelos-axioms})}
  The destination (``superclass'') of a specialization inherits all
  instances of its source (``subclass'').
\end{axiom}

  An example is the specialization \#8: all instances
of {\tt Manager} (including
          {\tt mary} are also instances
of {\tt Employee}.
O-Telos enforces {\bf typing} of the
attribute values by the following general axiom:


\begin{axiom}{Instantiation axiom (axiom 14 in appendix \ref{cha:otelos-axioms})}
If p is a proposition that is instance of a proposition P then the source
of p must be an instance of the source of P, and the destination of p must
be an instance of the destination of P.
\end{axiom}

For example, ``{\tt Mary Smith}'' must be an instance of {\tt String}. The individual
{\tt mary} also shows another feature: attribute classes specified at the class
level do not need to be instantiated at the instance level. This is the
case for the {\tt boss} attribute of {\tt Employee}. On the other hand, they may be
instantiated more than once as e.g.\ {\tt dept}.


In some cases for attribute categories occuring in a frame the
corresponding objects which are instantiated by the concrete attributes,
can not uniquely be determined\footnote{Subsection \ref{sec:CBL} contains an
  example for this problem in the context of linking logical formulas
  to O-Telos objects.}. This multiple generalization/instan\-tia\-tion
problem is solved\footnote{For specialization relationships between
  two objects we need an axiom similar to the instantiation axiom
  which requires specialization relationships between their sources
  and destination components. \cite{jeus92} contains the complete
  axiomatization.} by the following condition which must hold for
O-Telos databases:


\begin{axiom}{Multiple generalization/instantiation axiom (axiom 17 in appendix \ref{cha:otelos-axioms})}
  If p1 and p2 are attributes of two classes c1 and c2 which have the
  same label component l, and i is a common instance of c1 and c2
  which has an attribute with category l, then there must exist a
  common specialization c3 of c1 and c2 with an l labelled attribute
  p3 which specializes p1 and p2, and i is instance of c3.
  Particularly if c1 is specialization of c2 and p1 is specialization
  of p2, c1 and p2 already fulfill the conditions for c3 and p3.
\end{axiom}

O-Telos treats all three kinds of relationships ({\tt attribute}, {\tt isa}, {\tt in}) as
objects. Thus each attribute, instantiation or generalization link of
{\tt Employee} may have its own attributes and instances.  For example, each of
the four {\tt Employee} attributes is an instance\footnote{These
  instantiations were left out in the set of propositions for the
  employee example above.} of an attribute class denoted by the label
{\tt attribute} but can also have instances of its own. The attribute with
label {\tt earns} of {\tt mary} is an instance of attribute {\tt salary} of class
{\tt Employee}. Syntactically, attribute objects are denoted by appending
the attribute label with an exclamation mark to the name of some
individual. The relationship between {\tt salary} and {\tt earns} could be
expressed as


\begin{verbatim}
mary!earns in Employee!salary
end
\end{verbatim}

Instantiation links are denoted by the operator ''\verb/->/'' and specialization links by 
''\verb/=>/''. They should always be enclosed in parentheses:

\begin{verbatim}
(mary->Manager)
end

(Manager=>Employee)
end
\end{verbatim}

The operators can be combined to form complex expressions.
The next example shows how to reference the instantiantion link
between the attribute {\tt mary!earns} and its attribute class {\tt Employee!salary}.
The second frame shows that arbitrarily complex expressions are possible.
The parentheses have to be used to make the operator expressions unique. The attribution operator
''\verb/!/'' has a stronger binding than the instantiation and specialization operators.
According to our own experience, complex expressions for denoting objects are rare in modeling.
It is good to know that any object in O-Telos can be
uniquely referenced in the frame syntax.

\begin{verbatim}
(mary!earns->Employee!salary) with
  comment
    com1: "This is a comment to an instantiation between attributes"
end

(mary!earns->Employee!salary)!com1 with
  comment
   com2: "This is a comment to the the previous comment attribute"
end

\end{verbatim}


The labels {\tt InstanceOf}, {\tt IsA} and {\tt Attribute} for the three Telos system
classes are indeed alias names for the following object expressions:

\begin{verbatim}
Attribute   <--->  Proposition!attribute
InstanceOf  <--->  Proposition->Proposition
IsA         <--->  Proposition=>Proposition
\end{verbatim}

Hence, {\tt Attribute} as the alias name for the attribute with label {\tt attribute} of
{\tt Proposition}. {\tt InstanceOf} is the alias name for the instantiation link between
{\tt Proposition} and {\tt Proposition}. The object {\tt Proposition} is indeed an instance
of itself because it has the shape of an individual object, which is a special case of
the shape of a proposition. Finally, {\tt IsA} is an alias name for the specialization link
between {\tt Proposition} and {\tt Proposition}. This representation is deviates
slightly from the axioms in appendix \ref{cha:otelos-axioms} because it was originally
implemented in ConceptBase in this way. The reflexive definition of {\tt InstanceOf}
({\tt IsA}) as instantiation (specialization) links is redundant since O-Telos axioms 18-22
derive these instantiations anyway.


