O-Telos propositions have a temporal component: the transaction time%
\footnote{The original specification of Telos has two temporal components. The
{\em valid time\/} and the {\em transaction time}. The valid time is defined as
the time interval when the statemment made by a Telos proposition is true in the world.
The transaction time is the time when this statement is part of the knowledge base.
O-Telos skipped the valid time because it is virtually impossible to have a
tractable implementation of Allen's interval calculus \cite{All83},
when in interplays with deductive rules. Earlier versions
of ConceptBase until version 3.1 did however implement both time components.}.
The transaction time of a proposition is not assigned by the user but by the system at
the the time of an update (TELL, UNTELL, RETELL). ConceptBase uses right-open
and closed predefined time intervals. Right-open time intervals are represented like
in the subsequent example: 

\begin{verbatim}
P(#mary,#mary,mary,#mary,tt(millisecond(1992,1,11,17,5,42,102),
                            infinity))
\end{verbatim}


The object {\tt mary} is believed since 17:05:42 on January 11, 1992. The
label 'infinity' denotes that the end time of the object lies in the
future and is not yet known. In any case, the current time '{\it now}' is regarded
to be smaller than 'infinity'.
Right-open transaction times indicate objects that are part of the ``current'' knowledge base.

Closed intervals (denoted by binary tt-terms) indicate ``historical'' objects, i.e.\
objects that have been untold.
Example:

\begin{verbatim}
  P(#E1,#mary,*instanceof,#M,tt(millisecond(1992,1,11,17,5,42,0),
                                millisecond(1995,12,31,23,59,59,999))
\end{verbatim}

The object {\tt \#E1}, i.e. the instantiation  of {\tt mary} to the class {\tt Manager}
is believed from 17:05:42 on January 11, 1992, until the end of the last millisecond
of the year 1995. We call the first component of the transaction time also the start time
object and the second component the end time.
Start and end time of an object can be retrieved by the predicates {\tt Known},
and {\tt Terminated} (see section \ref{sec:CBL}).
Transactions in ConceptBase usually add or terminate several propositions. At the begin
of the transaction, ConceptBase reads the current time and uses it to set
the transaction time of all affected propositions. Consequently, all inserted propositions get
the same start time of their transaction time and all terminated propositions
get the same end time of their transaction time. The database does not change between two transactions,
hence the finite sequence of transaction times can be used to enumerate all updates
to the database. Examples on how to inspect the database using the transaction time are in
the CB-Forum at \url{http://merkur.informatik.rwth-aachen.de/pub/bscw.cgi/1921789}.




\section{Rules and constraints}
\label{sec:CBL}

The ConceptBase predicative language CBL [JK90] is used to express
integrity constraints, deductive rules and queries. The variables inside
the formulas have to be quantified and assigned to a ``type'' that limits the
range of possible instantiations to the set of instances of a class.
ConceptBase offers a set of predicates for the predicative language defined
on top of an O-Telos database as visible for a given rollback time,
i.e.\  $\OB_{rbt}$ for some {\tt rbt}. Any rule, constraint or
query is run against $\OB_{rbt}$ rather than the full database {\OB}.



\subsection{Basic predicates}
The following predicates
provide the basic access to an O-Telos database. Some have both an
infix and a prefix notation. As usual we employ the object identifer to refer to an object.


\begin{enumerate}
\item {\tt (x in c)} or {\tt In(x,c)}\\
The object {\tt x} is an instance of class {\tt c}.
\item {\tt (c isA d)}  or {\tt Isa(c,d)}\\
The object {\tt c} is a specialization (subclass) of {\tt d}
\item {\tt (x m y)} or {\tt A(x,m,y)}\\
The object {\tt x} has an attribution link to the object  {\tt y} and this link
has the attribute category  {\tt m}.
Structural integrity demands that the label {\tt m} belongs to an attribute of a class
of {\tt x}.
\item {\tt Ai(x,m,o)}\\
The object {\tt x} has an explicit attribute {\tt o}. This attribute is instance of
an attribute category with label {\tt m}.
\item {\tt (x m/n y)} or {\tt AL(x,m,n,y)}\\
The object {\tt x} has an attribution link labelled {\tt n} to the object  {\tt y}. The attribution has the
category {\tt m}.
\item {\tt From(p,x)}\\
The object {\tt p} has source {\tt x}.
\item {\tt To(p,y)}\\
The object {\tt p} has destination {\tt y}.
\item {\tt Label(p,l)}\\
The object {\tt p} has label {\tt l}. If {\tt l} is used as a variable, it must be quantified over the
class {\tt Label}.
\item {\tt P(p,x,n,y)}\\
There is an object {\tt P(p,x,n,y)} in the database $\OB_{rbt}$.
\item {\tt Known(p,t)}
The object {\tt p} is known in $\OB_{rbt}$  since {\tt t}, i.e.\ an object {\tt P(p,x,n,y,tt)} is
part of the database OB and {\tt t} is the start time of {\tt tt}. The argument
{\tt t} is a string of the format \verb+"tt(millisecond(yr,mo,d,h,min,sec,millisec))"+.
It is regarded as an instance of the class {\tt TransactionTime}.
\item {\tt Terminated(p,t)}
The object {\tt p} is unknown in $\OB_{rbt}$ after {\tt t}, i.e.\ an object {\tt P(p,x,n,y,tt)} is
part of the database OB and {\tt t} is the end time of {\tt tt}. The argument
{\tt t} is represented like with {\tt Known}.
An object that has not yet been untold has the end time \verb+"tt(infinity)"+.
\item {\tt (x [in] mc)} or {\tt In2(x,mc)}\\
The object {\tt x} is an instance of class {\tt c} and {\tt c} is an instance of class {\tt mc}.
In other words, {\tt (x [in] mc)} is equivalent to 
{\tt exists c/VAR (x in c) and (c in mc)}
\item {\tt (x [m] y)} or {\tt A2(x,m,y)}\\
The object {\tt x} and {\tt y} are linked by an attribute {\tt a1}. 
The attribute {\tt a1} is an instance of an attribute {\tt a2}
which itself is an instance of an attribute {\tt a3} with label {\tt m}.
The predicate is equivalent to the formula
{\tt exists c,d,n/VAR (x in c) and (y in d) and (c m/n d) and (x n y)}.
\end{enumerate}

The predicates {\tt In2} and {\tt A2} are also called {\em macro predicates} since they are standing
for sub-formulas. They are fully supported in constraints of query classes.
The predicate {\tt A2} is not yet supported for deductive rules and integrity constraints
due to limitations of the formula compiler. You can use the {\tt AL} predicate instead.
Examples on using macro predicates are available from the CB-Forum
(\url{http://merkur.informatik.rwth-aachen.de/pub/bscw.cgi/877047}). They are
also discussed in more detail in section \ref{sec:mlm}.


The relation of the above predicates and the P-facts of the database is defined by the O-Telos
axioms (appendix \ref{cha:otelos-axioms}). For example, axiom 7 states
$$
\forall ~o,x,n,y,p,c,m,d ~P(o,x,n,y) \land P(p,c,m,d) \land \In(o,p)
        \Rightarrow AL(x,m,n,y)
$$
So, if an attribute object {\tt o} of an object {\tt x} is an instance
of an attribute object {\tt p} of the object {\tt c}, then {\tt AL(x,m,l,y)} (also
written as {\tt (x m/n y)} can be derived. This axiom provides those solutions to
the {\tt AL} predicate that are directly based on P-facts. Further solution can be derived
via user-defined deductive rules. The other predicates are based on P-facts as well.
The {\tt Ai} predicate is for historical reasons not included in the list of axioms.
It is defined as
$$
\forall ~o,x,n,y,p,c,m,d ~P(o,x,n,y) \land P(p,c,m,d) \land \In(o,p)
        \Rightarrow Ai(x,m,o)
$$

There are a few variants for the predicates for instantiation, specialization and attribution 
to check whether a fact is actually stored or deduced: 

\begin{enumerate}
\item {\tt In\_s(x,c)}\\
The object {\tt x} is an explicit instance of class {\tt c}.
\item {\tt In\_e(x,c)} or {\tt :(x in c):}\\
The object {\tt x} is an explicit instance of class {\tt c}, or of one of the
 sub-classes of {\tt c}, or of the system class of {\tt x}. The system class of
individual objects is {\tt Individual}, attribution objects  have the system class {\tt Attribute},
instantiation objects the system class {\tt InstanceOf}, and specialization objects have the system
class {\tt IsA}.
\item {\tt A\_e(x,m,y)}or {\tt :(x m y):}\\
The objects {\tt x} and {\tt y} are linked by an explict attribute with attribute category {\tt m}.
The attribute category is either explicitly assigned to the attribute or derived by a rule (see 
subsection \ref{sec:aepred}).
\item {\tt Isa\_e(c,d)}or {\tt :(c isA d):}\\
The class {\tt c} is a direct subclass of class {\tt d}.
\end{enumerate}

The above predicates can be used, for example,
to define defaults values (see
\url{http://merkur.informatik.rwth-aachen.de/pub/bscw.cgi/2396075})
Since deduction should be transparent to the user,
one should avoid using the above predicates if the proper predicates {\tt In(x,c)} and
{\tt A(x,n,y)} can do the job.


\subsection{Notes on attribution}
The attribution of objects in O-Telos (axioms 7 and 8 in appendix \ref{cha:otelos-axioms})
is more generic than in object-oriented approaches,
in particular UML. In O-Telos, an attribution relates two arbitrary objects. In languages such as UML,
attributes are defined at classes to declare which states an object (instance of the class) may
have. This is well possible in O-Telos as well, e.g. by declaring the integer-valued {\tt salary} attribute
of a class {\tt Employee} and using it for instances of the class. However, O-Telos does not
restrict attributes to just values. The target of an attribute can be any object. Hence, the
concept of an attribute in O-Telos is the generalization of an UML association and an UML attribute.
A second difference is that an O-Telos attribute has essentially several labels tagged to it: its own
label (object label) and the labels of its attribute categories (class labels). 
The latter are the labels of the attributes declared
at the classes of an object, the first is the label of the attribution at the level of the object
that has the attribute. We illustrate this subsequently.

Attributes at the instance level are instances of attributes at the class level 
(=attribute categories). An attribute category at the class level can be instantiated
several times at the instance level. For example, consider the frame for {\tt Mary}:

\begin{verbatim}
mary in Manager with
  name,aliasname
    hername: "Mary Smith"
  salary
    earns: 15000
  dept
    advises:PR;
    currentdept:RD
end
\end{verbatim}

The object {\tt mary} has four attributes with object labels 
{\tt hername}, {\tt earns}, {\tt advises}, and {\tt current\-dept}.
The attribute categories are {\tt name}, {\tt aliasname}, {\tt salary}, and {\tt dept}. The last category
is instantiated twice. ConceptBase uses the following predicate facts (infix variant of the AL predicate)
to express the content of the frame:

\begin{verbatim}
(mary in Manager)
(mary name/hername "Mary Smith")
(mary aliasname/hername "Mary Smith")
(mary salary/earns 15000)
(mary dept/advises PR)
(mary dept/currentdept RD)
\end{verbatim}

So, there are four attributes using four attribute categories. Like an object can have multiple classes,
an attribute can have multiple categories. In fact, explicit attributes in O-Telos are just
objects and their attribute categories are their classes. 
At the lowest abstraction level (tokens), 
the object labels of the attributions frequently do not carry a specific meaning and
can then be neglected when formulating logical expressions. 
The attribution predicate {\tt (x m y)} performs just this projection.
In the example, the following attributions facts are true:

\begin{verbatim}
(mary name "Mary Smith")
(mary aliasname "Mary Smith")
(mary salary 15000)
(mary dept PR)
(mary dept RD)
\end{verbatim}

The class labels {\tt name}, {\tt aliasname} etc.\ are defined at an abstraction level where
the meaning of some application domain is captured. 
The class label (attribute category) of an attribute is
defined as an object label of an attribute at the class level. For example, the {\tt name}
and {\tt aliasname} attributes could be defined for the class {\tt Employee} as follows:

\begin{verbatim}
Employee in Class with
   attribute,single
      name: String
   attribute
      aliasname: String
end
\end{verbatim}

Here, the following predicate facts would be true:

\begin{verbatim}
(Employee in Class)
(Employee attribute/name String)
(Employee single/name String)
(Employee attribute/aliasname String)
(Employee attribute String)
(Employee single String)
\end{verbatim}

The mechanism for attribution is exactly the same as for instances like {\tt mary}. 
Note that the 3-argument attribution predicate expressing {\tt (mary name "Mary Smith")} 
represents a meaningful statement for some reality to be modeled. 
On the other hand, the predicate fact {\tt (Employee attribute String)} is much less significant
because the label {\tt attribute} does not transport a specific domain meaning. Here, the 4-argument
attribution predicate such as used for the fact {\tt (Employee attribute/name String)}
is required. Still, from a formal point of view, there is no different treatment of
predicates at the class and instance level.
This uniformity is the basis for meta-modeling, i.e. the definition of modeling
languages by means of meta classes.
The class labels
{\tt attribute} and {\tt single} need to be defined at the classes of {\tt Employee}. Those are
{\tt Class} and the pre-defined class {\tt Proposition}, to which any object including {\tt Employee}
and {\tt mary} is instantiated. In this case, both {\tt attribute} and {\tt single} are defined 
for {\tt Proposition}:

\begin{verbatim}
(Proposition attribute/attribute Proposition)
(Proposition attribute/single Proposition)
\end{verbatim}

Note that {\tt attribute} has itself as category. This is the most generic attribute category and
applies to any (explicit) attribution. 

Both the attribution predicate {\tt (x m y)} and its long form {\tt (x m/n y)} can be derived,
i.e. occur as conclusion of a deductive rule. In such cases, there are no explicit attribute
objects between {\tt x}  and {\tt y}. ConceptBase demands, that in such cases one of the classes
of {\tt x}  has an attribute with label {m}. Deductive rules for {\tt (x m/n y)} are
introduced with ConceptBase V7.1. They allow to simulate multi-sets, i.e. derived attributes
where the same value can occur multiple times. 
Examples are available in the CB-Forum
(\url{http://merkur.informatik.rwth-aachen.de/pub/bscw.cgi/2330042}).

\subsection{Assigning attribute categories to explicit attributes}
\label{sec:aepred}

The instantiation of an explicit attribute to an attribute category can be explicit (see above), 
or via inheritance, or via a user-defined rule.  
Explicit instantiation is typically established when telling a frame
like the {\tt Employee} example to the database. {\em Instantiation by inheritance\/} is more rarely
used but is in fact just the application of the specialization principle to attribution objects:

\begin{verbatim}
  Employee with
     attribute
       salary: Integer
  end
  Manager isA Employee with
     attribute
        bonus: Integer
  end
  Manager!bonus isA Employee!salary end
\end{verbatim}


Here, the {\tt bonus}  attribute is declared as specialization of the {\tt salary} attribute. Any 
instance of the {\tt bonus} attribute will then be an instance of the {\tt salary} attribute via
the usual class membership inheritance of O-Telos.  For example,

\begin{verbatim}
  mary in Manager with
     bonus
       bon1: 10000
  end
\end{verbatim}

shall make the following attribution facts true:

\begin{verbatim}
(mary bonus/bon1 10000)
(mary bonus 10000), A_e(mary,bonus,10000)
(mary salary/bon1 10000)
(mary salary 10000), A_e(mary,salary,10000)
(mary attribute/bon1 10000)
(mary attribute 10000), A_e(mary,attribute,10000)
\end{verbatim}

The third method to instantiate an explicit attribute to an attribute category is via 
a {\em user-defined rule}.
We use the employee example again:

\begin{verbatim}
  Employee in Class with
     attribute
       salary: Integer;
       premium: Integer;
       country: String
     rule
       premrule: $ forall e/Employee prem/Employee!premium 
                      (e country "NL") and Ai(e,premium,prem)
                    ==> (prem in Employee!salary) $
  end  
\end{verbatim}

Now, consider the following instances:

\begin{verbatim}
marijke in Employee with
  salary sal: 50000
  premium pr: 3000
  country ctr: "NL"
end
\end{verbatim}

This makes the following attribution facts true:

\begin{verbatim}
(marijke salary/sal 50000)
(marijke salary 50000), A_e(marijke,salary,50000)
(marijke premium/pr 3000)
(marijke premium 3000), A_e(marijke,premium,3000)
(marijke salary/pr 3000)
(marijke salary 3000), A_e(marijke,salary,3000)
(marijke country/ctr "NL")
(marijke country "NL"), A_e(marijke,country,"NL")
\end{verbatim}

Hence, any explicit premium attribute of an employee of the Netherlands is regarded as an
explicit salary as well.

Note that the three cases discussed here are for {\em explicit\/} attribution objects. You may also
define rules that derive {\tt (x m y)} or {\tt (x m/n y)} directly. In such cases, there is no need
for an explicit attribute between {\tt x}  and {\tt y}. The attribution is complelety derived.


\subsection{Reserved words}

In order to avoid ambiguity, neither {\tt in} and {\tt isa} nor the
logical connectives {\tt and} and {\tt or} are allowed as attribute
labels\footnote{For the example of subsection \ref{sec:representation} among others the
  ground predicates {\tt (mary in Manager)}, {\tt (Manager isA
    Employee)} and {\tt (mary earns 15000)} are valid facts describing
  the contents of the database. We suggest to choose verbs (e.g. {\tt earns}
  in our example) for attribute labels to get more natural and
  readable predicates.}.
Likewise, names of predicates such as {\tt A}, {\tt Ai}, {\tt In} should not be used as object names
or variable names. The same holds for the keywords {\tt with} and {\tt end}, which are used in the
frame syntax.


\subsection{Comparison predicates}
The next predicates are second class citizens in formulas. In contrast to the
above predicates they cannot be assigned to classes of the O-Telos database
base. Consequently, they may only be used for testing, i.e. in a legal
formula their parameters must be bound by one of the predicates 1 - 8.

\begin{enumerate}
\item {\tt (x < y), (x > y), (x <= y), (x >= y)}\\
{\tt x} and {\tt y} may be instances of any class. If they are instance of {\tt Integer} or
{\tt Real}, they are ordered numerically. If they are instance of {\tt TransactionTime} they
are ordered according to the time they are representing (newer times are greater than older
times). Otherwise, they are ordered alphabetically.
\item {\tt (x = y)} \\
The objects {\tt x} and {\tt y} are equal. 
\item {\tt (x <> y)} or {\tt (x $\backslash$= y)}\\
The objects {\tt x} and {\tt y} are not the same. 
\end{enumerate}

All comparison predicates may use functional expressions as operands.
They are evaluated before the comparison predicates is evaluated. See
section \ref{sec:cqc} for examples.
The predicates {\tt (x == y)}, {\tt UNIFIES(x,y)} and {\tt IDENTICAL(x,y)} defined in earlier releases of ConceptBase are deprecated. It is recommended to use
{\tt (x = y)} instead.



\subsection{Typed variables}
The exact syntax of CBL is given in appendix \ref{cha:syntax}.
The types of variables
(i.e.\ quantified identifiers) are interpreted as instantiations:

\begin{itemize}
\item {\tt forall x/C F}  \hfill $\rightarrow$  \hfill {\tt forall x (x in C) ==> F} \hfill \hbox{}
\item {\tt exists x/C F}  \hfill $\rightarrow$  \hfill {\tt exists x (x in C) and F} \hfill \hbox{}
\end{itemize}

The class {\tt C} attached to variable {\tt x} is called the {\em variable range}.
The anonymous variable range {\tt VAR} is treated as follows.

\begin{itemize}
\item {\tt forall x/VAR F}  \hfill $\rightarrow$  \hfill {\tt forall x F} \hfill \hbox{}
\item {\tt exists x/VAR F}  \hfill $\rightarrow$  \hfill {\tt exists x F} \hfill \hbox{}
\end{itemize}

Anonymous variable ranges are only permitted in meta formulas, see section \ref{sec:CCmeta}. 

\subsection{Semantic restrictions on formulas}
\label{sec:SemFormula}

We demand that each variable is quantified exactly once inside a formula.
This is no real restriction: in case of double quantification rename one of
the variables. More important is a restriction similar to static type
checking in programming languages that demands a strong relationship
between formulas and the knowledge base:

\begin{axiom}{Predicate typing condition}
(1) Each constant (= arguments that are not variables) in a formula F must be
the name of an existing object in the O-Telos database, or it is a
constant of the builtin classes Integer, Real, or String. 

(2) For each attribution predicate {\tt (x m y)} (or {\tt Ai(x,m,o)}, resp.) occuring in a formula there must be a
unique attribute labelled {\tt m} of some class {\tt c} of {\tt x} in the knowledge base, 
the so-called {\em concerned class}.

(3) For each instantiation predicate {\tt (x in c)}, the argument {\tt c} must be a constant.
\end{axiom}

All instantiation and attribution predicates need to be "typed" according
to the predicate typing condition.
Formally, we don't assign types to such predicates but 
{\em concerned classes}. Any instantiation predicate and any attribution
predicate in a formula must have a unique concerned class. It is determined as follows:

\begin{itemize}
\item The concerned class of an instantiation predicate {\tt (x in c)} is the class {\tt c}.
The argument {\tt c} may not be a variable.
\item The concerned class of attribution predicates {\tt (x m y)} and {\tt Ai(x,m,o)} is principally the most 
special attribute with label {\tt m} of all classes of {\tt x}%
\footnote{Since any object is an instance of {\tt Proposition}, ConceptBase will include this class
when searching the concerned class of an attribution predicate.}.
The O-Telos axioms listed in
appendix \ref{cha:otelos-axioms}, in particular axiom 17, make sure that there may 
not be more than one
candidate attribute if {\tt x} is the name of an existing object. If {\tt x}
is a variable, we demand that there is at most one candidate in the variable range of {\tt x}
and its superclasses.
If no class of x (i.e. also no superclass of any class of x) defines such an attribute
and the CBserver has been started with the predicate typing mode 'extended', then
the concerned class is determined from the subclasses of the classes of x. Theoretically,
one can choose the common superclass of all such attributes of subclasses of the classes of x (if existent).
However, ConceptBase currently demands that there must be a single such attribute in the 
subclass hierarchy. 
\end{itemize}


Example: The concerned class of {\tt (e boss b)}  in the {\tt SalaryBound} constraint in subsection
\ref{sec:rulesyntax} is the {\tt Employee!boss}. The class of variable {\tt e} is {\tt Employee}. This
is the most special superclass of itself and indeed defines the attribute {\tt Employee!boss}.

The purpose of the predicate typing condition is to allow ConceptBase to compile
attribution predicates {\tt (x m y)} to an internal form {\tt Adot(cc,x,y)} that
replaces the attribute label {\tt m} by the object identifier {\tt cc} of the concerned class. 
This enourmously speeds up the computation of predicate extensions. 
A similar effect is applicable to instantiation predicates. Here, the
concerned class of {\tt (x in c)}  is {\tt c}. Another effect of the
predicate typing condition is that certain semantically meaningless 
predicate occurrences are detected at compile time. For example,
{\tt (x m y)} can only have a non-empty extension, if some class of
{\tt x} defines an attribute with label {\tt m}. 

If the argument {\tt x} in a predicate {\tt (x m y)} is a variable, 
then the initial class of {\tt x} is determined by the the variable range
in the formula. The variable {\tt this} of query class constraints
can have multiple initial classes, being the set of superclasses of the 
corresponding query class.
All superclasses of {\tt c} are also regarded as classes of {\tt x}. 
If {\tt x} is a constant, then the classes of {\tt x} are determined by a query to the database.
A formula violating the first clause of the predicate typing condition would make a
statement about something that is not part of the database. As an example,
consider the following formula:


{\tt forall x/Emplye not (x boss Mary)}


With the example database of section \ref{sec:representation}, we find two errors: There are no
objects with names {\tt Emplye} and {\tt Mary}.

There are two possible cases to violate the second part of the restriction.
The first case is illustrated by an example:

{\tt forall x/Proposition y/Integer (x salary y) ==> (y < 10000)}

In this case the classes of x, Proposition and any of its superclasses,
have no attribute labelled salary. Therefore, the predicate (x salary y)
cannot be assigned to an attribute of the database. Instead, one has to specify

{\tt forall x/Employee y/Integer (x salary y) ==> (y < 10000)}

  or

{\tt forall x/Manager y/Integer (x salary y) ==> (y < 10000)}

depending on whether the formula applies to managers or to all employees.

The second clause of the predicate typing condition is closely related to multiple
generalization/instan\-tia\-tion. Suppose, we add new classes {\tt Shop},
{\tt Guest} and {\tt GuestEmployee} to the given class {\tt Employee}:


\begin{verbatim}
Shop in Class
end

Guest in Class with
      attribute
            dept: Shop
end

GuestEmployee in Class isA Guest,Employee
end
\end{verbatim}

The following formula refers to objects of class {\tt GuestEmployee}
and their dept attribute. The problem is that two different
attributes, {\tt Employee!dept} and {\tt Guest!dept}, apply as
candidates for the predicate {\tt (x dept PR)}:


{\tt forall x/GuestEmployee (x dept PR) ==> not (x in Manager)}


In order to solve this ambiguity, we demand that in such cases a common
subclass exists that defines an attribute dept which conforms to both
definitions, e.g.

\begin{verbatim}
Shop in Class
end

GuestEmployee with
        attribute
                dept: ShopDepartment
end

ShopDepartment in Class isA Shop,Department
end
\end{verbatim}


The third clause of the predicate typing condition is forbidding instantiation
predicates with a variable in the class postion. The restriction is a pre-condition
for an efficient implementation of the incremental formula evaluator of ConceptBase.
Without a constant in the class position of {\tt (x in c)} any update of the instances
of any class matches the predicate. Hence, ConceptBase would need to re-evaluate the
formula that contains the predicate. Since any update (TELL,UNTELL,RETELL) is 
containing instantiation facts, any formula with an unrestricted predicate {\tt (x in c)}
has to be re-evaluated for any update. This inefficiency can be avoied by demanding
that the class position is a constant. A relaxation to this clause (and clause 2) is
discussed in sub-section \ref{sec:CCmeta}.



When compiling the frames, ConceptBase will make sure that the
attribute {\tt GuestEmployee!dept} is specializing the two {\tt dept}
attributes of {\tt Shop} and {\tt Department}. As a consequence,
the attribution predicate {\tt (x dept PR)} can be uniquely attached to its so-called
{\em concerned class\/} {\tt GuestEmployee!dept}.

The predicate typing condition holds for all formulas, regardless whether
they occur as constraints or rules of classes or within query classes%
\footnote{The enforcement of the restriction has been extended to query classes
as of ConceptBase release 6.1. To support applications that were written
for earlier releases, a CBserver option {\tt -cc} (predicate typing) has been introduced to
disable the check for query classes. Details are in section \ref{cha:cbserver}.
With ConceptBase 7.2 (March 2010), the predicate typing has been further extended
and now will scan subclasses of of the classes of x in attribution predicates
(x m y) in case that superclasses do not provide a matching attribute class.
You need to set the CBserver option {\tt -cc} to 'extended' to activate this behavior.
The extended mode creates more cases that the predicate type (=concerned class)
is found. It should be noted that objects like x that are not instance
of a class that defines and attribute with label m will lead to a failure
of the predicate (x m y), i.e. its negation is then true.}%
.


\subsection{Rule and constraint syntax}
\label{sec:rulesyntax}
A legal {\em integrity constraint\/} is a CBL formula that fulfills predicate typing
condition. A legal {\em deductive rule\/} is a CBL
formula fulfilling the same condition and having the format:

{\tt forall x1/c1 ... xn/cn R ==> lit(a1,...,am)}

where
\begin{itemize}
\item {\tt lit} is a predicate of type 1 or 3, and
\item the variables in {\tt a1,...,am} are contained in {\tt x1,...,xn}
\end{itemize}

In O-Telos, rules and constraints are defined as attributes of classes. Use
the category {\tt constraint} for integrity constraints, and the
category {\tt rule} for deductive rules. The text of the formula has
to be enclosed by the character `{\tt \$}'.
The choice of the class for a rule or constraint is arbitrary (except
for query classes which use the special variable 'this').

Continuing our running example, the following formula is a deductive rule
that defines the {\tt boss} of an {\tt Employee}. Note that the variables
{\tt e,m} are both {\tt forall}-quantified.

\begin{verbatim}
Employee with
 rule
   BossRule : $ forall e/Employee m/Manager d/Department
                (e dept d) and (d head m)
                ==> (e boss m) $
 constraint
   SalaryBound : $ forall e/Employee b/Manager x,y/Integer
                (e boss b) and (e salary x) and (b salary y)
                   ==> (x <= y) $
end
\end{verbatim}

The second formula is an integrity constraint that uses the boss attribute
defined by the above rule. The constraint demands a {\tt salary} of an
{\tt Employee} does not exceed the {\tt salary} of his {\tt boss}. 
Note that you can define multiple  salaries for a given instance of
{\tt Employee}. The constraint is on each individual {\tt salary}, not
on the sum%
\footnote{Use multi-sets as discussed in
\url{http://merkur.informatik.rwth-aachen.de/pub/bscw.cgi/2330042} if
you want to constrain the sum of salaries.}%
! Also note that the arguments of the {\tt <=} predicate  are
bound by the two predicates with attribute label {\tt salary}.

\subsection{Meta formulas}
\label{sec:CCmeta}

Some formulas violating the predicate typing condition can be re-written to a set
of formulas that do not violate the condition. The so-called {\em meta formulas\/} are
a prominent category of such formulas. They have occurrences of predicates
with so-called {\em meta variables}. There are two cases. First, an instantiation
predicate {\tt (x in c)}, {\tt :(x in c):}, or {\tt In\_s(x,c)} where the class
argument {\tt c} is a variable.
Second, an attribution predicate {\tt (x m y)} or {\tt :(x m y):} where the
label argument {\tt m} is a variable.
In such cases, the concerned class cannot be determined directly
even though the formula as such is meaningful. 
ConceptBase relies on predicate typing for the sake of efficiency and static stratification.
The concerned class is internally used as predicate name. This increases the selectivity
and reduces the chance on non-stratified deduction rules. Fortunately, all meta formulas
can be re-written to formulas fulfilling the predicate typing condition. The re-writing 
replaces the meta variables by all possible value. Since all variables are bound to finite classes,
the re-writing yields a finite set of formulas. However, if a meta variable is bound to
a class with a large extension, the re-writing will also yield a large set of generated
formulas.

Meta formulas allow to specify assertions
involving objects from different levels and hence
significantly improve flexibility of O-Telos models.
An example for the usage of meta formulas can be found
in the appendix \ref{sec:ER-diagrams} where
the enforcement of constraints in ER diagrams
is solved in an elegant way.

As instructional example, assume we want to define that a certain attribute category {\tt M}
is transitive, i.e.\ if {\tt (x M y)} and  {\tt (y M z)}, then {\tt (x M z)} shall hold.
Many attribute categories are supposed to be transitive, for example the {\tt ancestor}
relation of persons, or the {\tt connection} relation between cities in a railway network.

The following meta formula defines transitivity once and forever:

\begin{verbatim}
Proposition in Class with
  attribute
     transitive: Proposition
  rule
     trans_R: 
     $ forall x,y,z,M/VAR 
          AC/Proposition!transitive 
          C/Proposition
           P(AC,C,M,C) and (x in C) and 
           (y in C) and (z in C) and
           (x M y) and (y M z) ==> (x M z) $
end
\end{verbatim}

The rule is a meta formula because {\tt C} and {\tt M} are meta variables. In this case, one
can re-write the formula by replacing all possible fillers for {\tt AC}, i.e. by the instances
of {\tt Proposition!transitive}. A filler for {\tt AC} will determine fillers for {\tt C} and
{\tt M} since the first argument of a proposition {\tt P(AC,C,M,C)} is identifying the proposition.

As a consequence, one can define the ancestor relation to be transitive by simply telling

\begin{verbatim}
Person in Proposition with
  transitive
     ancestor: Person
end
\end{verbatim}

ConceptBase will match the attribute {\tt Person!ancestor} with the variable {\tt AC} in 
the above meta formula. This yields {\tt P(Person!ancestor,Person,ancestor,Person)},
which binds the meta variable {\tt C} to {\tt Person} and {\tt M} to {\tt ancestor}.
The resulting generated formula is:

\begin{verbatim}
    forall x,y,z/VAR  (x in Person) and (y in Person) and (z in Person)
            and (x ancestor y) and (y ancestor z)
                        ==> (x ancestor z)
\end{verbatim}

which can be shortened to

\begin{verbatim}
    forall x,y,z/Person (x ancestor y) and (y ancestor z)
                        ==> (x ancestor z)
\end{verbatim}

The technique to generate such 'shortened' formulas is called {\em partial evaluation}.
Its input are facts like {\tt (Person!ancestor in Proposition!transitive)} and
the output are formulas that specialize the original meta formulas for the case
of the input facts.

The above formula is fulfilling the O-Telos predicate typing condition. 
Likewise, the connection relation of cities gets transitive via:

\begin{verbatim}
City in Proposition with
  transitive
     connection: City
end
\end{verbatim}

The advantage of meta formulas is that they save coding effort by re-using them in
different modelling contexts. If a meta formula is linked to an attribute category
(like {\tt transitive} in the example above, then the semantic of several such
attribute category can be combined by just specifying that a certain attribute
has multiple categories. Assume for example that we have defined acyclicy with a 
similar meta formula:

\begin{verbatim}
Proposition in Class with
  attribute
     acyclic: Proposition
  constraint
     acyclic_IC: 
     $ forall x,y,M/VAR
              AC/Proposition!acyclic
              C/Proposition
                P(AC,C,M,C) and (x in C) and 
                 (y in C) and 
                 (x M y)  ==> not (y M x) $
end
\end{verbatim}

Then, the {\tt ancestor} attribute can be specified to be both transitive and acyclic by

\begin{verbatim}
Person in Proposition with
  transitive,acyclic
     ancestor: Person
end
\end{verbatim}

The more categories like {\tt transitive} and {\tt acyclic} are defined with meta formulas,
the greater is the productivity gain for the modeler. Not only does it save coding effort.
It also reduces coding errors since formula specification is a difficult task.
Meta formulas are a natural extension to classical metamodeling. They allow to specify the
meaning of modeling constructs at the meta class level. The mapping to simple formulas
allows an efficient evaluation. It also allows to retrieve the specialized semantics definition
of a model (instance of a metamodel) since the generated simple formulas are attached to
the constructs of the model (in the example above they are attached to classes {\tt Person}
and {\tt City}). The meta formula compiler is fully incremental, i.e.\ if the database
is updated, then the set of generated simple formulas is also updated if necessary. For example,
if one removes the category {\tt transitive} from the {\tt connection} attribute of {\tt City}, then
the generated simple formula will also be removed.

Meta formulas that contain meta variables under existential quantification cannot be compiled
directly, but there is an elegant trick to circumvene this restriction. Consider for example
the formula:

\begin{verbatim}
$ forall x/VAR SC/CLASS spec/ISA_complete 
     (spec super SC) and (x in SC) ==>
      exists SUBC/CLASS (spec sub SUBC) and (x in SUBC) $
\end{verbatim}

The meta variable {\tt SUBC} is under an existential quantifier. To circumvene the problem,
we write an intermediary rule replacing the predicate {\tt (x in SUBC)}:

\begin{verbatim}
$ forall x/Proposition spec/ISA SUBC/CLASS
     (spec sub SUBC) and (x in SUBC) ==> (x inSubRel SUBC) $
\end{verbatim}

and then re-write the original constraint to

\begin{verbatim}
$ forall x/VAR SC/CLASS spec/ISA_complete 
     (spec super SC) and (x in SC) ==>
     exists SUBC/CLASS (spec sub SUBC) and (x inSubRel SUBC) $
\end{verbatim}

So essentially, we pass the meta variable to the condition of the intermediary rule.
The attribute {\tt inSubRel} is just used to be able to specify a dedicated conclusion
predicate for the intermediary deductive rule. It is defined as attribute of
{\tt Proposition}. The complete example is at
\url{http://merkur.informatik.rwth-aachen.de/pub/bscw.cgi/d3070600/mp-ISA-complete.sml.txt}.


Many more re-usable examples for meta formulas are in the ConceptBase-Forum at
\url{http://merkur.informatik.rwth-aachen.de/pub/bscw.cgi/1042523}.

\subsubsection{Tell order for meta formulas}

Meta formulas are compiled by ConceptBase using the partial evaluation strategy.
Facts matching certain predicates of the meta formula trigger
the partial evaluation, which then leads to new formulas that need to be compiled
by ConceptBase. In certain cases, the generated formulas are themselves meta formulas,
that need to be further partually evaluated when other matching facts are 
inserted to the system. 

The implementation of the incremental compilation suggests that the meta formula
and the input facts should not be defined in the same TELL transactions. 
When creating your models that involve meta formulas, you should put the
definition of the meta formula in a different file than the class/object
definitions hat utilize the meta formulas. It may also be wise to store the
definitions in different modules (see section \ref{sec:module}). Specifically, the
meta formulas should be defined in a super-module of the modules that use these definitions.




\subsection{Further object references}
\label{sec:ObjRef}

In addition to the so called {\em select expressions}
{\tt !,=>,->} already introduced above
for directly refering to attributes, specializations
and instantiations as objects,
three other basic constructors may be used within
frames and assertions.

\begin{itemize}
\item $^\land$ is the counterpart of {\tt !} and
denotes the target of an attribute instead of the
attribute object itself, e.g.
{\tt mary}$^\land${\tt advises} is the same as {\tt PR}.
\item The set valued {\tt .} operator has the commonly
used meaning as in paths in object-oriented models
and relates an object with the set of all
attribute values of a certain category,
i.e.\ {\tt mary.dept} contains both {\tt PR} and {\tt R\&D}.
\item As {\tt .} can be understood as the set variant
of $^\land$ but employing the attribute {\em category}
instead of the concrete attribute label, the same
holds for {\tt |} (with respect to {\tt !}).
Thus {\tt mary|dept} is the set of all attributes (as objects)
that belong to category {\tt dept} and have source {\tt mary}.
\end{itemize}
Note, that {\tt .} and {\tt |} are only allowed
to occur within assertions whereever
classes may be interpreted as range restrictions,
e.g.\ in quantifications or at the right hand side
of {\tt in} predicates. The full syntax
which allows combinations of all basic constructors
can be found in the appendix. For illustration we
just give two examples here. The first is an alternative
representation for the rule above, the second
could be a constraint stating that all bosses of {\tt Mary}
earn exactly 50.000.

\begin{enumerate}
\item
{\tt forall e/Employee m/Manager (m in e.dept.head) ==> (e boss m)}.
\item {\tt forall b/Mary.dept.head (b salary 50000)}
\end{enumerate}


\subsection{User-definable error messages for integrity constraints}
\label{sec:ErrMessIC}

ConceptBase provides a couple of errors messages in case of an
integrity violation. These errors messages refer to the logical
definition of the constraint and are sometimes hard to read.
To provide more readable error messages, one can attach so-called {\em
hints\/} to constraint definitions. These hints are attached as comments
with label {\tt hint} to the attribute that defines the constraint.

Consider the salary bound constraint above. A hint could look like:

{\small
\begin{verbatim}
Employee!SalaryBound with
 comment
   hint: "An employee may not earn more than her/his manager!"
end
\end{verbatim}
}

It is also possible to attach hints to meta-level constraints.
In this case, the hint text can refer to the meta-level variables
occuring in the meta-level constraint. These variables will be
replaced by the correct fillers when the meta-level constraint is
utilized in some modeling context.

Assume, for example, we want to have a symmetry category and
attach a readable hint to it:

{\small
\begin{verbatim}
Proposition with
  attribute
    symmetric: Proposition
end

RelationSemantics in Class with
  constraint
 symm_IC: $ forall AC/Proposition!symmetric C/Proposition x,y/VAR M/VAR
                     P(AC,C,M,C) and (x in C) and (y in C) and
                     (x M y)  ==> (y M x) $
end

RelationSemantics!symm_IC with
 comment
   hint: "The relation {M} of {C} must be symmetric,
          i.e. (x {M} y) implies (y {M} x)."
end
\end{verbatim}
}

Note that the references to the {\em meta variables}%
\footnote{Meta variables are those variables that occur in the class position
of (x in c), or in the label position of (x m y) or Label(x,m). In the running example,
C and M are meta variables.}\/
 {\tt M} and {\tt C} are surrounded by curly braces,
and that these meta variables are also occurring in the meta-level constraint.
Now, use the {\tt symmetric} concept in some modeling context, e.g. to define
that the {\tt marriedTo} attribute of {\tt Person} should be symmetric:

{\small
\begin{verbatim}
Person with
  attribute,symmetric
   marriedTo: Person
end
\end{verbatim}
}

At this point of time, ConceptBase will find the hint text for the symmetric
constraint and will adapt it to the context of {\tt C=Person} and {\tt M=marriedTo}.
When an integrity violation occurs, the {\em substituted\/} hint

\begin{verbatim}
    "The relation marriedTo of Person must be symmetric,
     i.e. (x marriedTo y) implies (y marriedTo x)."
\end{verbatim}

will be presented to the user. An example violation is:

{\small
\begin{verbatim}
bill in Person with
  marriedTo m1: eve
end

eve in Person end
\end{verbatim}
}

One can also define a hint for the meta-level constraint that
refers only to a (non-empty) subset of the meta variables.
If a hint for a meta formula cannot be substituted as shown avove,
ConceptBase will not issue the hint but rather the text of the generated
formula.

Examples of user-defined error messages can be found in the ConceptBase-Forum at
\url{http://merkur.informatik.rwth-aachen.de/pub/bscw.cgi/1543277}.


\subsection{Immutable properties}
\label{sec:Immutable}

Immutable attributes cannot be changed (retold) once they are
defined for their respective source object. For example, the two spouses in a marriage
contract cannot be changed once the marriage contract object has been created.
Key attributes in the entity relationship model are another example. Once an
entity gets its key, the key may never be changed. Of course, the object as a whole
can be removed.

ConceptBase provides an attribute category for such objects:

{\small
\begin{verbatim}
Proposition with
  attribute
    immutable: Proposition
end
\end{verbatim}
}


The semantics cannot be expressed by a static integrity constraint but by an active rule
that guards the deletion of immuntable attributes. See also
\url{http://merkur.informatik.rwth-aachen.de/pub/bscw.cgi/d3452001/Immutable.sml.txt}
in the CB-Forum. The immutable attribute category is predefined in ConceptBase,
but the active rule implementing its semantics is not. Include it from the CB-Forum
and add it to your source models when needed. The definition below shows the use of
immutable attributes. The spouses are created when the source
object {\tt marriage1} is created. Afterwards, they shall not be updated for the whole
time span of {\tt marriage1}.

{\small
\begin{verbatim}
Marriage in Class with  
  immutable
    spouse1 : Person;
    spouse2 : Person
end 

marriage1 in Marriage with  
  spouse1 s1 : mary
  spouse2 s2 : bill
end 
\end{verbatim}
}

The immutable attribute category instructs the integrity constraint compiler to prune unnecessary
integrity checks on updates of these attributes. This feature can be disabled by setting the
CBserver parameter {\tt-o} to a value smaller than 4, see also section \ref{sec:cbsparams}.




\section{Query classes}
\label{sec:CBQL}

ConceptBase realizes queries as so-called query classes, whose instances 
fulfill the membership constraint of the query \cite{stau90}. 
This section first defines the
structural properties of the query language CBQL and then introduces the
predicative component. Queries are instances of a system class {\tt QueryClass}
which is defined as follows:

{\small
\begin{verbatim}
QueryClass in Class isA Class with
     attribute
         retrieved_attribute: Proposition;
         computed_attribute: Proposition
     attribute,single
         constraint: MSFOLquery
end
\end{verbatim}
}

A super classes of query class imposes a range condition of the set of possible instances of
the query class: any instance of the query class must be an instance of the superclass.
Example: ``socially interested'' are those
managers that are member of a union.

{\small
\begin{verbatim}
Union in Class
end

UnionMember in Class with
    attribute
        union:Union
end

SI_Manager_0 in QueryClass isA Manager,UnionMember
end

QueryClass SI_Manager in QueryClass isA Manager,UnionMember with
     retrieved_attribute
         union: Union;
         salary: Integer
end
\end{verbatim}
}

Super classes themselves may be query classes, which is the
first kind of query recombination. The second frame shows the feature of
{\bf retrieved attributes} which is similar to projection in relational algebra.
Example: one wants to see the name of the union and the salary of socially
interested managers. The attributes must be present in one of the
super-classes of the query class. In this example, the {\tt union} attribute is
obviously inherited from the class {\tt UnionMember} and {\tt salary} is inherited from
{\tt Manager}.  CBQL demands that retrieved attributes are necessary: each answer
must instantiate them. If an object does not have such an attribute then it
will not be part of the solution. As usual with attribute inheritance, one
may specialize the attribute value class, e.g.

{\small
\begin{verbatim}
QueryClass Well_off_SI_Manager isA SI_Manager with
     retrieved_attribute
         salary: HighSalary
end

HighSalary in Class isA Integer with
     rule
       highsalaryrule: $ forall m/Integer
                           (m >= 60000)
                                 ==> (m in HighSalary) $
end

\end{verbatim}
}

The new attribute value class {\tt HighSalary} is a subclass of {\tt Integer} so that
each solution of the restricted query class is also a solution of the more
general one. It should also be noted that {\tt HighSalary} also could have been
another query class. This is the second way of query recombination.

Retrieved attributes and super-classes already offer a simple way of
querying a knowledge base: projection and set intersection. For more
expressive queries there is an predicative extension, the so-called {\bf query
constraint}.
We use the same many-sorted predicative language as in section \ref{sec:CBL}
for deductive rules and integrity constraints and introduce  a useful
abbreviation:


Let {\tt Q} be a query class with a constraint {\tt F} that contains the predefined
variable {\tt this}. Then, the query class is essentially an abbreviation for the two deduction rules

        {\tt forall this  F' ==> Q(this)}

        {\tt forall this  Q(this) ==> (this in Q)}

The deduction rules are generated by the query compiler and only listed here for
discussing the meaning of a query class.
The variable {\tt this} stands for any answer object of {\tt Q}. We call {\tt this}
also the answer variable.  The sub-formula {\tt F'} is combined from the query 
constraint {\tt F} and the structural properties of the query, in particular the super-classes
and the retrieved attributes. Each super-class {\tt C} of {\tt Q} contributes a 
condition {\tt (this in C)} to the sub-formula {\tt F'}. Each retrieved attribute
like {\tt a:D} contributes a condition {\tt ((this a v) and (v in D))}
to {\tt F'}. Moreover, each retrieved attribute add the new argument {\tt v} to the predicate
{\tt Q}.
The following example shows the translation.

{\small
\begin{verbatim}
QueryClass Well_off_SI_Manager1 isA SI_Manager with
     retrieved_attribute
         union: Union
     constraint
         well_off_rule: $ exists s/HighSalary
                        (this salary s) $
end
\end{verbatim}
}

The generated deduction rules for this query class are:

{\small
\begin{verbatim}
       forall this,v
          (this in SI_Manager) and
          (this union v) and (v in Union) and
          (exists s (s in HighSalary) and (this salary s))
       ==> Well_off_SI_Manager1(this,v)

       forall this,v Well_off_SI_Manager1(this,v) 
       ==> (this in Well_off_SI_Manager1)
\end{verbatim}
}


Classes occuring in a query constraint may be query classes themselves, e.g. {\tt HighSalary}.
This is the third way of query recombination. 

The next feature introduces so-called {\bf computed attributes}, i.e.\ 
attributes that are defined for the query class itself but
not for its super-classes. The assignment of values for the solution is
defined within the query constraint. 
Like retrieved attributes, computed attributes are included in the answer predicate
so that the proper answer can be generated from it.

The following example defines a computed attribute \verb+head_of+ that stands for
the department a manager is leading. The attribute {\tt head\_of} is
supposed to be computed by the query. It is not an attribute of
{\tt SI\_Manager} or its super-classes. We expect that and answer
to the query includes the computed attribute. Note that a reference
\verb+~head_of+  to the computed attribute occurs inside the query constraint.

{\small
\begin{verbatim}
QueryClass Well_off_SI_Manager2 isA SI_Manager with
     retrieved_attribute
         union: Union
     computed_attribute
         head_of: Department
     constraint
         well_off_rule: $ exists s/HighSalary
                    (this salary s) and
                    (~head_of head this) $
end
\end{verbatim}
}

The variable \verb+~head_of+ in the constraint
is prefixed with \verb+~+ to indicate that it is a placeholder for the compted attribute
with label \verb+head_of+. We recommend to
use the prefix to avoid confusion of the placeholder variable in query constraints and corresponding
attribute label in the query definitions. Analogously, you can use the prefixed answer variable
\verb+~this+ instead of the plain version \verb+this+. ConceptBase will
accept both the prefixed and the non-prefixed version for the answer variable and the
placeholder variable of computed attributes. Non-prefixed placeholders in constraints are
replaced internally by the prefixed counterparts.

The generated deduction rules for above query would be:

{\small
\begin{verbatim}
       forall this,v1,v2
          (this in SI_Manager) and
          (this union v1) and (v1 in Union) and
          (v2 in Department) and
          (exists s (s in HighSalary) and (this salary s) 
                     and (v2 head this))
       ==> Well_off_SI_Manager2(this,v1,v2)

       forall this,v1,v2 Well_off_SI_Manager2(this,v1,v2) 
       ==> (this in Well_off_SI_Manager2)
\end{verbatim}
}

Computed attributes are treated differently from retrieved attributes. The retrieved
attribute {\tt union} causes the inclusion of the condition
{\tt (this union v1) and (v1 in Union)}. The corresponding variable {\tt v1} does not occur
in the sub-formula generated for the query class constraint. The computed attribute
causes the inclusion of the condition {\tt (v2 in Department)} but typically also occurs in the
query constraint.
Like retrieved attributes computed attributes are necessary, i.e. any
solution of a query with a computed attribute must assign a value for this
attribute. 
There is no limit in the number of retrieved and computed attributes. The more of them are
defined for a query class, the more arguments shall the answer predicate have.


Recursion can be introduced to queries by using recursive deductive rules
or by refering recursively to query classes. The example asks for all
direct or indirect bosses of {\tt bill}:


{\small
\begin{verbatim}
QueryClass BillsMetaBoss isA Manager with
     constraint
         billsBosses:
            $ (bill boss this) or
              exists m/Manager
                (m in BillsMetaBoss) and
                (m boss this)$
end
\end{verbatim}
}


Further examples can be found in the directory

\begin{center}
\verb+$CB_HOME/examples/QUERIES+.
\end{center}

Queries are represented as O-Telos classes and consequently they can be
stored in the knowledge base for future use. It is a common case that one
knows at design time {\bf generic queries} that are executed at run-time with
certain parameters. CBQL supports such parameterizable queries:

{\small
\begin{verbatim}
GenericQueryClass isA QueryClass with
     attribute
        parameter: Proposition
end
\end{verbatim}
}

Generic queries are queries of their own right: they can be evaluated.
Their speciality is that one can easily derive specialized forms of them by
substituting or specializing the parameters. An important property is that each solution of
a substituted or spezialized form is also a solution of the generic query. This is a
consequence of the inheritance scheme. The example shows that parameters can
also be retrieved and computed attributes. Note, that variable
for the parameter in the constraint is prefixed here with \verb+~+; you may also
omit the prefix in the constraint as explained above).

{\small
\begin{verbatim}
What_SI_Manager in GenericQueryClass isA Manager,UnionMember with
     retrieved_attribute,parameter
        salary: HighSalary;
        union: Union
     computed_attribute,parameter
        head_of: Department
     constraint
        well_off_rule: $ (~head_of head this) $
end
\end{verbatim}
}

There are two kinds of specializing generic query classes:


\begin{enumerate}
\item Specialization of  a parameter {\tt [a:C']}

Example: \verb+ What_SI_Manager[salary:TopSalary]+

In this case {\tt TopSalary} must be a subclass of {\tt
  HighSalary}. The solutions are those managers in \verb+ What_SI_Manager+
that not only have a high but a top salary.
\item Instantiation of a parameter {\tt [v/a]}

Example: \verb+What_SI_Manager[Research/head_of]+

The variable \verb+head_of+ is the replaced by the constant {\tt Research} (which must
be an instance of {\tt Department}).
\end{enumerate}

One may also combine several specializations, e.g.
\begin{verbatim}
         What_SI_Manager[salary:TopSalary,Research/head_of].
\end{verbatim}

The specialized queries can occur in other queries in any place where
ordinary classes can occur, e.g.

{\small
\begin{verbatim}
110000 in Integer end
QueryClass FavoriteDepartment isA Department with
     retrieved_attribute
         head: What_SI_Manager[110000/salary]
end
\end{verbatim}
}

Parameters that don't occur as computed or retrieved attributes are
interpreted as existential quantifications if they are not instantiated.
Note that parameters need to be known as objects before using them in
query calls.

\subsection{Query definitions versus query calls}
 \label{sec:qdefvscalls}

Telling a frame that declares an instance of {\tt QueryClass} (as well as its
sub-classes {\tt Generic\-Query\-Class}, and {\tt Function}) constitutes the
definition of a query. It shall be compiled internally into Datalog code not
visible to the user. Once defined, a query can be called simply by referring to
its name. Hence, if {\tt Q} is a the name of a defined query class, then {\tt Q}
is also an admissable query call. It results in the set of all objects that fulfill the
membership constraint of {\tt Q}. ConceptBase regards these objects as derived instances of
the query class {\tt Q}.

If a query class has parameters, then any of its specialized forms is also an admissable
query call. For example, if {\tt Q} has two parameters {\tt p1}, {\tt p2} in its
defining frame, then {\tt Q[v1/p1,v2/p2]} is the name of a class whose instances
is the subset of instances of {\tt Q} where the parameters {\tt p1} and {\tt p2} are
substituted by the values {\tt v1} and {\tt v2}. The substitution yields a simplified
membership constraint that precisely defines the extension of {\tt Q[v1/p1,v2/p2]}.

If a generic query class is called with all parameters substituted by fillers, then
one can omit the parameter labels. Assume that the query {\tt Q} has just the parameters
{\tt p1} and {\tt p2}. Then the expression {\tt Q[v1,v2]} is equivalent to {\tt Q[v1/p1,v2/p2]}.
ConceptBase uses the alphabetic order of parameter labels to convert the shortcut form
to the full form. 



\subsection{Query classes and deductive integrity checking} \label{sec:qcic}

ConceptBase regards query classes as ordinary classes with the
only exception that class membership cannot be postulated (via a TELL)
but is derived via the class membership constraint formulated for
the query class. A consequence of this equal treatment is that
a constraint formulated for an ordinary class can refer directly
or indirectly to a query class, e.g.:

{\small
\begin{verbatim}
Unit in Class with
  attribute
    sub: Unit
end
BaseUnit in QueryClass isA Unit with
  constraint
    c1: $ not exists s/Unit!sub From(s,~this) $
end
SimpleUnit in Class isA Unit with
  constraint
    c: $ forall s/SimpleUnit (s in BaseUnit) $
end
\end{verbatim}
}

Here, the constraint in the class {\tt SimpleUnit} refers to
the query class {\tt BaseUnit}.

ConceptBase supports references to query classes without parameters%
\footnote{If the CBserver option {\tt -cc} is set to off, we also allow
calls to generic query classes in rules and constraints. In such cases,
incremental integrity checking will be incomplete and thus potentially wrong. Only experienced
users should employ them.}
in ordinary class constraints and rules.
A prerequisite is that the the query class is an instance of the builtin class
{\tt MSFOLrule}. Membership to this builtin class is necessary to
store the generated code for an integrity constraint (or a rule that an
integrity constraint might depend upon) and to enable the creation of
a dependency network between the query class and the integrity constraints.
There are two simple methods to achieve membership to {\tt MSFOLrule}.

{\bf Method 1: }Make sure that any query class is an instance of {\tt MSFOLrule}.
This can simply be achieved be telling the following frame prior to your model:

{\small
\begin{verbatim}
QueryClass isA MSFOLrule end
\end{verbatim}
}


{\bf Method 2: } Decide for each query class individually.
You tag only those query classes that are used in rules or
constraints. This individual treatment saves some code generation at
the expense of being less uniform.
Such an individual tagging would look like

{\small
\begin{verbatim}
BaseUnit in QueryClass,MSFOLrule isA Unit with
  constraint
    c1: $ not exists s/Unit!sub From(s,~this) $
end
\end{verbatim}
}

ConceptBase will reject an integrity constraint or rule if it refers to
a query class that is not an instance of {\tt MSFOLrule}.

If a query class is defined as instance of {\tt MSFOLrule}, then it should not
have a meta formula as constraint! This is a technical restriction that can
easily be circumvened by using normal deductive rule.

For example, instead of the query class 

{\small
\begin{verbatim}
UnitInstance in QueryClass,MSFOLrule isA Proposition with
  constraint
     c1: $ (~this [in] Unit) $
end
\end{verbatim}
}

you should define

{\small
\begin{verbatim}
UnitInstance in Class with
  rule
     r1: $ forall x/VAR (x [in] Unit) ==> (x in UnitInstance) $
end
\end{verbatim}
}

The example uses the macro predicate {\tt (x [in] Unit)} explained earlier in this section. 
It is equivalent to the sub-formula {\tt exists c (x in c) and (c in Unit)}.



\subsection{Nested query calls and shortcuts} \label{sec:cqc}

ConceptBase has capabilities to form nested expressions from
generic query classes. The idea is to combine them like nested
functional expressions, e.g. $f(g(x),h(y))$.
The problem is however that queries stand for predicates and
nested query calls are thus formally higher-order logic
(predicates occur as arguments of other predicates),
and consequently outside Datalog. Still, the feature is so useful
that we provide it. A nested query call is like an ordinary
parameterized query call except that the parameters can themselves be
query calls. For example, {\tt COUNT[What\_SI\_Manager[10000/salary]/class]}
counts the instances of the parameterized query call
{\tt What\_SI\_Manager[10000/salary]}.
Syntactically, query calls can be arbitrarily deep, e.g.

{\small
\begin{verbatim}
Union[Intersec[EmpMinSal[800/minsal]/X,
               EmpMaxSal[1400/maxsal]/Y]/X,
      Manager/Y]
\end{verbatim}
}

ConceptBase does perform the usual type check on the parameters by analyzing
the instantiation of the {\em core class\/} of a query call. For example, the core class
of {\tt EmpMinSal[800/minsal]} is {\tt EmpMinSal}. Thus, ConceptBase will
check whether {\tt EmpMinSal} is an instance of the class expected for the
parameter {\tt X}.

Nested query calls are mostly used in combination with functional expressions, i.e.\
nested query calls where queries are functions (see section \ref{sec:functions}).
A function in ConceptBase is a query class that has at most one answer object
for any combination of input parameters.
Of particular interest for nested query calls are functions that do not
operate on values (suchs as integers) but rather on classes such as the class of all
employees with more than two co-workers. ConceptBase provides a collection
of aggregate functions that operate on classes. For example, the {\tt COUNT}
function returns the number of instances of a class. The input of such a function
can be any nested query call.

{\small
\begin{verbatim}
QueryClass EmployeeWith2RichCoworkers isA Employee with
  constraint
    c2: $ (COUNT[RichCoworker[this/worker]/class] = 2) $
end
\end{verbatim}
}

The outer predicate
(here: {\tt COUNT}) is an instance of {\tt Function}, i.e. delivers
at most one value for the given argument. It is also possible that
both operands of a comparison predicate are nested expressions:

{\small
\begin{verbatim}
QueryClass EmployeeWithMoreRichCoworkersThanWilli isA Employee with
  constraint
    c2: $ (COUNT[RichCoworker[this/worker]/class] >
           COUNT[RichCoworker[Willi/worker]/class]) $
end
\end{verbatim}
}

ConceptBase supports shortcuts for query calls and function calls
(see section \ref{sec:functions}) in case that
all parameters of a query (or function) have fillers in the query call. In such cases,
one can write {\tt Q[x1,x2,...]} instead of {\tt Q[x1/p2,x2/p2,...]}. ConceptBase shall
replace the actual parameters {\tt x1,x2} etc. for the parameter labels {\tt p1,p2}
in the {\em alphabetic order\/} of the parameter labels. For example, the expression 
{\tt RichCoworker[this]} is equivalent to {\tt RichCoworker[this/worker]} since
{\tt worker} is the only parameter label of the query. Likewise, 
{\tt COUNT[c]} is a shortcut for {\tt COUNT[c/class]}. Since {\tt COUNT} is also
a function, we support {\tt COUNT(c)} as well to match the usual notation for function
expressions. The last query class is thus equivalent to:

{\small
\begin{verbatim}
QueryClass EmployeeWithMoreRichCoworkersThanWilli isA Employee with
  constraint
    c2: $ (COUNT(RichCoworker[this]) > COUNT(RichCoworker[Willi])) $
end
\end{verbatim}
}

Since the {\tt COUNT} function is frequently used, ConceptBase provides the
shortcut {\tt \#c} for {\tt COUNT(c)}. Consequently, the shortest form of the
above query would be:

{\small
\begin{verbatim}
QueryClass EmployeeWithMoreRichCoworkersThanWilli isA Employee with
  constraint
    c2: $ (#RichCoworker[this] > #RichCoworker[Willi]) $
end
\end{verbatim}
}

The shortcut is also applicable to the {\tt Union} example above. The
expression below computes the numbers of instances of the set expression.

\begin{verbatim}
#Union[Intersec[EmpMinSal[800],EmpMaxSal[1400]],Manager]
\end{verbatim}

The definitions for {\tt Union} and {\tt Intersec}  can be found in
the ConceptBase-Forum at
\url{http://merkur.informatik.rwth-aachen.de/pub/bscw.cgi/896920}.

Besides {\tt COUNT}, ConceptBase supports aggregation function for
finding the minimum, maximum and average of a set. Aggregation functions are
not limitered to numerical domains. For example, one can define a function
that returns an arbitrary instance of a class:

{\small
\begin{verbatim}
selectrnd in Function isA Proposition with
  parameter
    class: Proposition
end
\end{verbatim}
}

The membership constraint has to be provided as so-called CBserver plug-in, see chapter 
\ref{cap:lpi}.
A call 
\begin{verbatim}
   selectrnd(RichCoworker[Willi/worker])
\end{verbatim}
would then return an arbitrary instance
of {\tt RichCoworker[Willi/worker]}. Random functions can be useful in the context
of active rules (section \ref{sec:eca}), e.g.\ to initiate the firing of a 
rule with an arbitrary candidate out of the set of candidates.
The code for {\tt selectrnd} is accessible via the ConceptBase-Forum at
\url{http://merkur.informatik.rwth-aachen.de/pub/bscw.cgi/1694234}.


\subsection{Reified query calls} \label{sec:reifiedquery}

You might want to memorize certain query calls that you want to call over and over again.
ConceptBase provides a built-in class {\tt QueryCall}, which you can instantiate by
such query calls as ordinary objects, i.e. {\em reified query calls}.
The following example defines the class count as a query call object:

\begin{verbatim}
   COUNT[Class/class] in QueryCall end
\end{verbatim}

Of course, you can ask the query call {\tt COUNT[Class/class]} without having told it as
an object. Reifying {\tt COUNT[Class/class]} additionally allows you to use it as an attribute of
another object, or to browse it with the graph editor.
Examples for query calls, in particular for using integer intervals as class attributes,
are available in the CB-Forum at
\url{http://merkur.informatik.rwth-aachen.de/pub/bscw.cgi/2571997}.


\section{View definitions}
\label{sec:views}

The view language of ConceptBase is an extension of the ConceptBase
Query Language CBQL.
Besides some extensions that allow an easier definition of queries, views
can also be nested to express n-ary relationships between objects.

The system class {\tt View} is defined as follows:

{\small
\begin{verbatim}
Class View isA GenericQueryClass with
attribute
    inherited_attribute : Proposition;
    partof : SubView
end
\end{verbatim}
}

Attributes of the category \verb+inherited_attribute+ are similar to
retrieved attributes of query classes, but they are not necessary
for answer objects of the views, i.e. an object is not required to have
a filler for the inherited attribute for being in the answer set
of the view.

The {\tt partof} attribute allows the definition of complex nested
views, i.e. attribute values are not only simple object names, they
can also represent complex objects with attributes.
The following view retrieves all employees with their departments,
and attaches the head attribute to the departments.

{\small
\begin{verbatim}
View EmpDept isA Employee with
retrieved_attribute, partof
    dept : Department with
        retrieved_attribute
            head : Manager
    end
end
\end{verbatim}
}

As the example shows, the definition of a complex view is straightforward:
for the ``inner'' frame the same syntax is used as for the outer frames.
The answers of this view are represented in the same way, e.g.

{\small
\begin{verbatim}
John in EmpDept with
dept
    JohnsDept : Production with
        head
            ProdHead : Phil
    end
end

Max in EmpDept with
dept
    MaxsDept : Research with
        head
            ResHead : Mary
    end
end
\end{verbatim}
}

To make the definition of views easier, we allow some shortcuts
in the view definition for the classes of attributes.

For example, if you want all employees who work in the same
departments as {\tt John}, you can use the term \verb+John.dept+
instead of {\tt Department}. In general, the term \verb+object.attrcat+
refers to the set of attribute values of {\tt object} in the attribute
category {\tt attrcat}. This path expressions may be extended to
any length, e.g.\ \verb+John.dept.head+ refers to all managers of
departments in which John is working.

A second shortcut is the explicit enumeration of allowed attribute
values. The following view retrieves all employees, who work
in the same department as John, and earn 10000, 15000 or 20000 Euro.

{\small
\begin{verbatim}
View EmpDept2 isA Employee with
retrieved_attribute
    dept : John.dept;
    salary : [10000,15000,20000]
end
\end{verbatim}
}


As mentioned before, ``inner'' frames use the same syntax as normal
frames. You can also specify constraints in inner frames which
refer to the object of an outer frame.

{\small
\begin{verbatim}
View EmpDept_likes_head isA Employee with
retrieved_attribute,partof
    dept : Department with
        retrieved_attribute, partof
            head : Manager with
                constraint c : $ A(this,likes,this::dept::head) $
        end
    end
end
\end{verbatim}
}

The rule for using the variable ``this'' in nested views is, that
it always refers the object of the main view, in this case an employee.
Objects of the nested views can be referred by {\tt this::label}
where {\tt label} is the corresponding attribute name of the nested view.
In the example, we want to express that the employees must like
their bosses. Because the inner view for managers is already part of
the nested view for departments we must use the double colon twice:
{\tt this::dept} refers to the departments and {\tt this::dept::head}
refers to the managers.

If you reload the definition of a view into the Telos Editor,
the complex structure of it is lost. During compilation of the view,
the view is translated into several classes and some additional
contraints are generated, so the resulting objects might look quite
strange if you reload them.

